				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">[An] alternative to the per pixel and per scanline is to do the "catch up" method. You execute CPU cycles until an event happens that needs the PPU to catch up, at which point you execute your PPU emulation to run PPU cycles until it catches up to the CPU. In the end it's up to you to decide what works best for you.</div>
<br />Catch-up is a threading method, thus it's orthogonal to PPU emulation granularity. You can do per-frame, scanline, pixel with catch-up, green threads, etc.
<br />
<br />You can also do per-pixel with full CPU timing accuracy even with a per-opcode CPU emulator by having it keep track of the times of memory accesses. For example, if a STA $2000 started at cycle count 10, then the $2007 write would be passed a cycle count of 13.</div>

